  "prompt": "Why does acetone break down cell membranes?",
  "response": "Acetone breaks down cell membranes primarily due to its chemical properties as a polar, aprotic solvent. Here's how it works:\n\n1. **Polarity**: Acetone is a polar molecule, meaning it has regions of partial positive and negative charges. This polarity allows it to interact with the polar regions of the phospholipids that make up cell membranes, disrupting their structure.\n\n2. **Lipid Solubility**: Acetone is highly miscible with lipids. Cell membranes are composed of a phospholipid bilayer, and acetone can dissolve these lipids, effectively breaking down the membrane.\n\n3. **Denaturation of Proteins**: Cell membranes also contain proteins that are essential for their structure and function. Acetone can denature these proteins by disrupting the hydrogen bonds and hydrophobic interactions that maintain their tertiary and quaternary structures. This denaturation further compromises the integrity of the cell membrane.\n\n4. **Disruption of Hydrophobic Interactions**: The hydrophobic tails of phospholipids in the cell membrane are held together by van der Waals forces. Acetone can penetrate these hydrophobic regions and disrupt these interactions, leading to the disintegration of the membrane.\n\n5. **Cell Lysis**: By dissolving the lipids and denaturing the proteins, acetone causes the cell membrane to lose its structural integrity, leading to cell lysis (rupture) and the release of cellular contents.\n\nIn summary, acetone's ability to dissolve lipids and denature proteins makes it highly effective at breaking down cell membranes. This property is why acetone is commonly used in biological research for cell lysis and in histology for tissue fixation and dehydration. However, it is also why acetone can be toxic to cells and organisms if exposure is significant.",
